# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: catamaran
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The 34th America's Cup was a series of yacht races held in San Francisco Bay in September 2013.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The series was contested between the defender Oracle Team USA team representing the Golden Gate Yacht Club, and the challenger Emirates Team New Zealand representing the Royal New Zealand Yacht Squadron.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The format was changed radically to a best of 17, and Oracle Team USA defended the America's Cup by a score of 9 to 8 after Team New Zealand had built an 8 to 1 lead.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand won the right to challenge for the Cup by previously winning the 2013 Louis Vuitton Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The 34th America's Cup's race schedule was the longest ever, in terms of number of days and number of races, and the first since the 25th America's Cup to feature both teams in a match point situation.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The Golden Gate Yacht Club defeated Société Nautique de Genève in the 2010 America's Cup to become the Defenders of the 2013 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The first Challenger of Record for the 34th Cup was Club Nautico di Roma, and a joint press conference was held on May 6, 2010, to plan for the event.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The planning process was to include a definition of new rules and an independent management team.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The Protocol for the 34th America's Cup was published on September 13, 2010.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] AC72 wing-sail foiling catamarans are being used for the America's Cup races and the AC45 class, a scaled-down one-design version of the AC72, was used for the preliminary training and racing until boats built to the AC72 rules became available.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The amended AC72 Class Rule version 1.1 was published on February 22, 2011.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The AC72 can reach speeds averaging about 30 knots (56 km/h; 35 mph) with peaks over 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph); that speed can be as much as 1.8 to slightly over twice the actual wind speed.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The previous America's Cup Class (ACC) boats reached speeds of 11 to 13 knots (20 to 24 km/h; 13 to 15 mph).
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] In order to increase global awareness and hence attract sponsors for the teams an America's Cup World Series was held over the 2011–12 and 2012–13 seasons.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The winner of each annual series was declared the America's Cup World Series Champion for that season.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] There were three regattas in 2011, five in 2012, and two in 2013.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Each regatta lasted for one week and had approximately six days of racing, including official practice.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Each AC World Series regatta was a combination of match and fleet racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] AC45 one-design catamarans were used for each World Series regatta.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Despite these measures the cost of mounting a competitive challenge exceeds US$100 million.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] In addition to using the AC45 catamarans for the initial world series races they are used in the nationality-based 'Youth America's Cup' (YAC).
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The smaller scaled down AC45 version of the AC72 with similar characteristics to the AC72 enables younger competition sailors to master the techniques used to sail this style of catamaran before they progress to the AC72 boats.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The YAC began in 2013, when both first and second places were taken by New Zealand entries.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The winning team included Peter Burling, Blair Tuke, Jono Spurdle, Sam Meech, Andy Maloney, Jason Saunders and Guy Endean.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] On July 8, 2010, Oracle Team USA announced that San Francisco was "the only city in the USA under consideration to host the 34th America's Cup” match.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] At the time, KGO-TV and *Gazzetta dello Sport*, an Italian sports newspaper, reported that Rome-Fiumicino, Italy was challenging San Francisco to host the event.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle Team USA confirmed that San Diego, Newport and Long Beach were considered earlier as possible venues for this event.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] A key parameter in deciding the venue was reliability of the wind and weather patterns so that pre-published television schedules would be virtually guaranteed to show racing rather than suffering endless postponements which was a significant problem for TV audiences watching the 2010 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] In early December 2010, BMW Oracle Racing became concerned that a full and final agreement with San Francisco would not be completed in time to comply with the requirement to announce the location of the cup venue on December 31, 2010.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] As a result, negotiations were activated with Newport, Rhode Island, as a potential venue for the cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] However, on December 31 San Francisco was officially awarded the right to host the 2013 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Initially fourteen yacht clubs submitted notices of entry within the deadline, but two were declined and ten withdrew.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Club Nautico di Roma was originally named as the Challenger of Record, but after their team Mascalzone Latino withdrew the Challenger of Record became the Royal Swedish Yacht Club, sponsoring Artemis Racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Other notable teams that withdrew included former Cup holder Alinghi and the Energy Team from Yacht Club de France.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] On August 2, 2012, the America's Cup Event Authority announced that four challenging teams would compete for the right to challenge Oracle Team USA, the only team that represented the defending Golden Gate Yacht Club.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Luna Rossa, a late entry, formed a partnership with Team New Zealand where they would share design and testing information.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Following Sail Korea's withdrawal in March 2013, the number of challengers dropped to three.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The course for the 34th America's Cup was specially designed to take advantage of the San Francisco Bay, to bring the racing within easy viewing of the shore for the first time.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The starting area was furthest away from the shore, close to the Golden Gate Bridge.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The boats were only allowed to enter the starting box two minutes before the usage of the starting gun.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The boat entering on port tack was allowed to enter ten seconds before the starboard tack boat.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This was to reduce the danger of having two boats travelling at up to 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph) heading towards each other into the starting area.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The length of the course varies, but is around 10 nautical miles (19 km; 12 mi) and generally takes about 25 minutes to complete.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] During the 2013 Louis Vuitton Cup on the same course, some races were raced with an extra lap around the leeward and windward gates.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This seven leg course is around 16 nautical miles (30 km; 18 mi), taking approximately 45 minutes to sail.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The racecourse was delineated by a boundary.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Going outside of the boundary draws a penalty which was indicated by blue lights on board the boats.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The green lights on board the boats flashed whenever the boat was within three boatlengths of the boundary, or a mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Whichever boat entered the three boatlength circle around a mark, had mark rights and was allowed to round without worrying about the other boat.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The exception was when there is an overlap between the two boats.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] If an overlap exists, room had to be made to ensure both boats round the mark safely.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The maximum time for a race is 40 minutes after which the race would be stopped.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] If a penalty was awarded against a boat, a moving penalty line was calculated and placed two boat lengths behind them, advancing on a direct heading to the mark or the wind (depending which leg).
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The penalised boat had to slow their Velocity Made Good such that their boat fell behind the penalty line.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This was calculated in real time by computers, and indicated to the teams on the water via the lights and direct radio communication.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Alcatraz Island was a unique part of the racecourse for this event.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] For the first week of the event, San Francisco Bay experienced flood tides during the America's Cup races.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] As water flowed into the bay, there was a cone close to the Island where the incoming tide was noticeably less than the rest of the racecourse.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] On the upwind leg, when boats had to sail against the flood tide, tactical use of this cone was crucial.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The challenger was determined in the 2013 Louis Vuitton Cup challenger selection series.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Emirates Team New Zealand won the Louis Vuitton Cup and therefore the right to challenge Oracle Team USA in the America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] An international jury found Oracle Team USA guilty of cheating during the America's Cup World Series warmup event in 2012 when they placed bags of lead pellets in their 45-foot catamarans to add additional weight outside of allowed areas.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Penalties imposed included expelling three team members, a $250,000 fine, and a one-point penalty for each of the first two races of the Match in which they would otherwise score a point.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This last penalty meant that Oracle had to win 11 races to retain the trophy, while New Zealand only needed to win 9 races to lift the cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The 34th America's Cup was held between challenger Team New Zealand and defender Oracle Team USA on a five-leg course on San Francisco Bay.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] One point was awarded for winning a race, and a total of nine points were needed to win the cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Due to the two race penalty assessed on Oracle Team USA, they needed 11 wins to defend the cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 1 Oracle's victories in races 4 and 8 did not award points, due to the penalty imposed by the jury.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 2 Oracle used their postponement card after race 5, canceling the second race scheduled for September 10.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 3 With Team New Zealand leading during the third leg, the second race on September 14 was abandoned by the race committee due to the wind exceeding the allowed maximum.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 4 September 16 was on the schedule as a reserve day and would have been used to make up for races already missed.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] However by agreement of both teams it was treated as a lay day.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 5 Both races on September 17, and the second races on both September 18 and September 19, were postponed due to the wind exceeding the allowed maximum beyond a reasonable start time.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 6 With Team New Zealand well ahead in light winds near the end of the fourth leg, the first race on September 20 was abandoned by the race committee due to the race exceeding the 40-minute time limit.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 7 Both races on September 21 were postponed by the race committee due to the wind direction not permitting a fair laying of the race course.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] 8 Due to the late start of race 16, a second race was not sailed on September 23 due to the 2:40pm cutoff time for racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The 34th America's Cup began in stark contrast to the one-sided races that dominated the 2013 Louis Vuitton Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand, skippered by Dean Barker, led at the first mark, and held the lead for the second leg, which was the first leg to be facing downwind.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle Team USA was 4 seconds behind Team New Zealand at the bottom mark, and during the upwind third leg the lead changed several times.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand led at the top mark by 25 seconds, and kept the lead until the finish line, winning by 36 seconds.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Race two began as the previous one ended, with Team New Zealand in front, despite the aggressive prestart by Oracle's skipper Jimmy Spithill.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand led the whole race, and completed the victory by 52 seconds to lead 0–2 in the overall scoreline.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle Team USA had better luck in the initial stages of Race three, as Spithill luffed Team New Zealand at the reach mark to successfully draw a penalty.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle held the lead for the first downwind leg, and were 18 seconds to the good heading into the upwind third leg.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The pivotal moment of the race occurred when Barker brought the New Zealand boat back on port tack within three boat lengths of the boundary.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle was forced to tack away due to the boundary rights, even though they were on starboard, which would have otherwise have had right of way.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The 29 second lead at the top mark was held by Team New Zealand all the way to the finish.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] They ultimately crossed the finish line 28 seconds ahead of Oracle, making the scoreline 0–3 to Team New Zealand.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Race four again started well for Oracle, leading around the reach mark by 6 seconds.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Although Barker pushed hard for the whole race, Spithill was able to hold off Team New Zealand, resulting in a finish 8 seconds ahead of Barker.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Due to the penalty imposed by the International Jury, Oracle did not score a point, leaving the New Zealand remaining 3 points ahead.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle lost race five by one minute and five seconds, after which the team used its Postponement Card to call off the scheduled second race.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand had once again been behind from the start all the way to the bottom of the race course.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] On the upwind leg, the New Zealand boat increased its speed relative to Oracle and took the lead.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] A top mark delta of 1:17 effectively ended the race, and gave Spithill plenty of time to consider his options.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The score at the end of the day was 0–4, to Team New Zealand.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Day four opened with the news that Oracle had changed their tactician.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] John Kostecki, who had raced on San Francisco Bay for decades, was dropped, and Sir Ben Ainslie, the skipper of Oracle's backup boat was brought on in his place.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Another change was the noticeably lighter winds compared to the earlier days of racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Race six followed a familiar refrain, with Oracle ahead at the start and holding that lead to the bottom of the downwind leg.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] After rounding the mark 12 seconds behind, Team New Zealand once again took over sailing into the wind.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The highest number of tacks seen thus far was unable to prevent Team New Zealand from gaining 55 seconds during the third leg, and the 44 second lead at the top mark was extended to 47 seconds at the finish.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand led from start to finish in Race 7.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] After a run of being behind at the start, Barker was strong in the windward position off the line and was able to beat Oracle Team USA by a substantial amount at the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Along with another substantial gain during the third leg, Oracle Team USA could not counter Team New Zealand's progress and finished a 1:06 behind.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand closed the day in a dominant position of 0–6.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] In race eight, Team New Zealand nearly capsized.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Leading from the start to midway up the third leg, Team New Zealand was tacking back to starboard to once again cover Oracle.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] However, a lack of hydraulic power at a crucial moment during the turn meant that the large wingsail did not move in time.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The boat's starboard hull rose out of the water and Aotearoa nearly capsized.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker was also penalised for failing to give way to Oracle, which was on starboard tack at the time.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The New Zealand boat followed Spithill to finish 52 seconds behind.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle's victory completed the penalty imposed by the International Jury, allowing them to accrue points for any subsequent victories.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand were ahead during the third leg of the day's second race, but it was abandoned by the Race Committee due to the wind exceeding the 22.6-knot (41.9 km/h; 26.0 mph) allowable maximum (23 knots (43 km/h; 26 mph) minus the 0.4 knots (0.74 km/h; 0.46 mph) tide).
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] In race nine, Oracle Team USA won from the start and extended its lead at each mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Spithill again won the start, and extended the lead at every mark including for the first time, a notable gain against the Kiwi boat on the upwind leg.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Recording consecutive victories for the first time allowed Oracle to obtain a point, with the score at 1–6.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand won race ten by 16 seconds; multiple reports described the race as among the most competitive of the series.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker looked to have been left behind by Spithill at the startline, but just managed to hold an overlap as the AC72s entered the three boat length circle at the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand took the 3 second lead, and increased it to 11 seconds at the second mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle again showed their new competitiveness during the upwind beat, and the lead changed three times.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] As the boats approached the top mark on split tacks, Barker slowed the boat, and then aimed down to pass under Oracle at speed.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The top mark split was only 1 second as Oracle rounded in front of the shore, and Aotearoa rounded the other mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] With the race still too close to call during the downwind leg, Spithill made the call to dip behind Team New Zealand rather than jibe.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The gap almost instantly became 100 metres.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker was able to hold this lead to the finish to take the series to 1–7.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] September 16 was scheduled as a reserve day.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] It would have been used to make up for races that had already been missed, however it was instead treated a rest day by agreement of both teams on the day.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The next schedule race day was September 17 however high winds resulted in a postponement.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Both teams were keen to race, and headed out to the starting area.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] However the start time for the first race was pushed back several times due to the 20.1-knot (37.2 km/h; 23.1 mph) wind limit, and with the wind continuing to increase, at 1:31 pm the Race Committee made the postponement official.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand led all the way to win race eleven by 15 seconds, to move to match point in the race for the Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] During the pre-start, Barker maneuvered in front of Spithill and then delayed both boats from crossing the start line until well after the gun had gone.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle performed well on the upwind beat, but Team New Zealand covered well, and the boats rounded opposite marks 17 seconds apart.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] At the final mark, Barker kept Aotearoa between Oracle and the mark, and the rounding was well below the usual speed.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand were able to accelerate away leaving Oracle almost stationary in the water on the sprint to the finish line, taking the score to 1–8.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The second race of the day suffered a 15-minute wind delay postponement.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The postponement came at the same as the boats hit the start line.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker had perfected a time on distance sprint to the line, to obtain a lead on the way to the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The boats made their way back to the starting area, but the wind and the strong outgoing tide combined to confirm the postponement of racing for the day.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker was aggressive in the pre-start phase of the first race of Day 9.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] It did not pay off, and Spithill was able to get into a position where Team New Zealand was forced to keep clear.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] From that lead off the start line, Oracle led the whole race to win race twelve by 31 seconds.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] During the upwind leg, Oracle's performance was excellent.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] They were able to sail on their foils at speeds approaching 32 knots (59 km/h).
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle gained their second point to take the score to 2–8.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The start time for the second race of the day was pushed back several times due to the wind exceeding the allowed limit.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] At one point the teams were able to enter the starting box, but the wind then exceeded the limit again.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Racing was then postponed for the day, allowing Oracle to keep alert for another day.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Day ten brought the lightest winds seen in the 34th America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The start of the first race was pushed back by five minutes, due to the need to shift one of the marks on the start line.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle had the better start in the 8-knot (15 km/h; 9.2 mph) winds, and luffed Team New Zealand at the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The first downward leg was very different from the rest of the racing, as neither boat was able to sail on its foils.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Aotearoa appeared to be the stronger boat in the light breeze, and rounded the leeward gate 1:42 ahead of the Americans.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The New Zealand boat continued to extend their lead during the third leg and the main concern turned to whether they would be able to cross the finish line within the 40 minute race limit.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Unfortunately for them, despite being ahead by more than 1,000 metres in winds of between 7 and 11 knots (13 and 20 km/h; 8.1 and 12.7 mph) near the end of the fourth leg, with 90% of the race complete, the time expired forcing the abandonment of the race.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The resail of race thirteen began at 2:33pm in 12 knots (22 km/h; 14 mph) of wind.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Spithill attempted to hook Barker during the pre start to gain advantage, but Barker managed to prevent Oracle from gaining the overlap.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand led over the line, and took a 3-second lead around the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The pivotal moment of the race came towards the end of the second leg.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand were slightly ahead and tried to cross in front of Oracle who had the starboard tack advantage.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Spithill had to evade the Kiwi boat, and gained a penalty for the infraction.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] With the boats still close heading into the leeward gate, Barker fluffed his lines, and Aotearoa ended up being forced to jibe twice in quick succession.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle sped away to begin the third leg leaving the Kiwis almost non-moving.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] That effectively caused the result the race, and Oracle confirmed their third point by 1:24 at the finish.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The New Zealanders' largest defeat of the Cup to date brought the score to 3–8.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] It had rained earlier in the day, with wind from the south, about 90 degrees from the desirable direction, at the time day eleven racing was scheduled to be undertaken.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The race committee pushed the start back several times, hoping that the wind would turn enough to allow racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This did not happen by the start cut off time, and weather again forced postponement of the day's racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Racing on the 22nd of September brought the America's Cup into its third week, equalling the previous longest regatta in Cup history, the 31st America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] A whale was also spotted in San Francisco Bay, bringing enough of a concern that it was tracked to ensure it would not affect racing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Race fourteen was another start-to-end win by Oracle.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Starting in the leeward position, Spithill again luffed Barker hard substantially past the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This set up a strong lead for the first downwind beat.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] On the upwind leg Team New Zealand were able to close the lead, and at one point had to dip under the American boat.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] However, they could not utilise the advantage to enough effect, and Oracle led well around the top mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand once again closed the lead about halfway down the fourth leg, but could not make the pass.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle won by 23 seconds, to bring the score to 4–8.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand led off the line for race fifteen, but the leeward position of the Oracle Team USA boat allowed them to round the reach mark first.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] A huge downwind leg from the American boat saw them round the leeward gate 1 minute ahead of Team New Zealand.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand did not give up, and were able to cut Oracle's lead in half by the windward gate, but were unable to make up the rest of the gap.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle had their best day in the race yet, winning both races to bring the score to 5–8.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The start of race sixteen was delayed for 30 minutes while the race committee waited for the wind to increase.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Emirates Team New Zealand took the leeward position at the start line but Oracle Team USA was able to sail on their foils, and sailed over on top of the New Zealand boat to lead by five seconds at the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] At the second mark, the New Zealand team were 13 seconds behind Oracle and after a tacking duel upwind to the third mark, Oracle was able to obtain the wind advantage for the downwind leg.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle sailed conservatively downwind gaining a 21-second lead for the fourth mark, which they extended to 33 seconds by finish line.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The earlier delay meant no second race for the day, as it would have exceeded the cutoff time of 2:40pm.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Race seventeen saw two penalties at the start against Emirates Team New Zealand.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] During the prestart, Dean Barker made his move too early, allowing Spithill to hook Barker.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle then took full advantage of their windward-leeward right of way, forcing Barker to attempt to stay out of the way.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Due to the extremely low boat speed at the time, Team New Zealand was unable to avoid the American boat, and there was contact between the two AC72s as a second penalty was awarded against the New Zealand boat.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] By the time the penalties had been completed, Oracle had accelerated away to find themselves ahead by 18 seconds at the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle built on this to obtain a 29-second lead to leeward gate, although this was trimmed to 19 seconds at the end of the third leg.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle went on to win by 27 seconds and cut Team New Zealand's lead to 7–8.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] "We're not going to stop--we're going to keep going all the way to the end", said Spithill.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker called this defeat "an absolute shocker" as he ended in "a really dead spot".
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] In race eighteen the New Zealand boat led at the start and up to the first mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] They set the speed record of the series, reaching 47.57 knots (24 m/s; 88 km/h; 55 mph) as they rounded the mark, to lead by 5 seconds.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] They kept the lead during the first downwind run, but Oracle took the lead at the first crossing on the upwind leg, after Team New Zealand made a poor tack.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand had starboard tack advantage and the lead at the time, but did not properly cover Oracle.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The American boat was sailing on their foils, and was able to sail past Team New Zealand without much difficulty.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle went on to lead by 57 seconds at the windward gate and kept the lead for the rest of race, winning by 54 seconds.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] This result tied the series 8–8 and forced a winner-take-all race.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Spithill called this win "very impressive" and said, "It gives us a lot of confidence going into tomorrow", saying that Wednesday will be "the most exciting day in the history of our lives.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The final day of the 34th America's Cup brought only the third winner-takes-all match in Cup history (previous such matches had occurred in 1920 and 1983).
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Barker and Spithill had also both moved into the top 5 all time America's Cup skippers during this regatta.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand had port entry advantage, and were able to convert this into the leeward position at the start line and a lead around the reach mark.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle had a moment where both bows dipped into the water, slowing them to open some separation between the two boats.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The first downwind leg saw both boats foiling at around 40 knots (74 km/h; 46 mph), at times well within 100 metres (330 ft) of each other.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand took the lead into the upwind third leg, but were unable to hold it.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle once again showed their upwind foiling ability and were able to pass.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Team New Zealand and Barker refused to give up, but in the absence of any mistakes from Oracle, they confirmed their victory 9–8 by 44 seconds on the line to the cheers of the crowd.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] At the press conference following the race, Barker said his team was "[feeling] pretty smashed, they are feeling it pretty bad", whilst Spithill said Team New Zealand were a "tough team".
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The power and speed of the catamarans used in the America's Cup has attracted criticism since the AC72 rule was announced.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Oracle's first AC72 pitch-poled in October 2012 after only eight days of sailing.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Though there were no injuries to the crew, the yacht was heavily damaged as the tide pulled it outside the bay into the Pacific Ocean.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] On May 9, 2013, Swedish team Artemis' first AC72 yacht flipped, resulting in the death of Olympic gold medalist Andrew James Simpson.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Stephen Barclay, CEO of the America's Cup Event Authority, promised a full inquiry into the events leading to Simpson's death and appointed a review committee to investigate both the Oracle and Artemis accidents, and to make recommendations for increasing the safety of the sailors.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The NBC Sports Group acquired the American television broadcast rights in 2012, making it the first time the race would be on network TV since 1992.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The first two races aired on NBC with subsequent races airing live on NBC Sports Network.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The races were also broadcast live and available on demand on the official America's Cup YouTube channel.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] To enhance television coverage, America's Cup officials developed LiveLine, a system that inserts graphics into live shots from helicopters similar to the first down line graphics system used on American football broadcasts.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] LiveLine would be used to show distance between boats, boat speed, course boundaries and marks, boat paths, wind speed and ocean current direction.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Race yachts carried military grade GPS tracking and telemetry systems to enhance the accuracy of measurements.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The system, developed by Sportvision, Inc., the America's Cup Event Authority, and NBC Sports Network, won the George Wensel Outstanding Technical Achievement Award at the 33rd Sports Emmy Awards.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Only moments after the win by Oracle Team USA, Hamilton Island Yacht Club in Queensland, Australia issued a challenge for the 2017 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] The challenge was accepted by the Golden Gate Yacht Club, which remained defender.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] Australian billionaire Bob Oatley was said to be financially backing the Hamilton Island Yacht Club as the Challenger of Record.
[src:catamaran/2013-america-s-cup] HIYC withdrew its challenge on 18 July 2014 and in November 2014 it was announced that Bermuda would host the 2017 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The 33rd America's Cup between Société Nautique de Genève defending with team Alinghi against Golden Gate Yacht Club, and their racing team BMW Oracle Racing was the subject of extensive court action and litigation, surpassing in acrimony even the controversial 1988 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Since the two parties were unable to agree otherwise, the match took place as a one-on-one deed of gift match in gigantic, specialized multi-hull racing yachts with no other clubs or teams participating.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Golden Gate Yacht Club swept the two races as their yacht *USA 17* powered by a rigid wing-sail proved to be significantly faster than Société Nautique de Genève's yacht *Alinghi 5*.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The litigation leading up to the match included which club would be the challenger, the dates and venue for the regattas, certain rules governing the regattas (in particular the measurement rules), and the construction of the boats.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Americans won back the Cup after they last lost it in 1995.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] When Société Nautique de Genève (SNG) successfully defended the trophy in the 32nd America's Cup, they immediately accepted a challenge from Club Náutico Español de Vela (CNEV) a Spanish organization formed expressly for the purpose of challenging for the cup and keeping the regatta in Valencia.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] When SNG and CNEV published their protocol for the 33rd America's Cup challenge, there was widespread consternation over its terms, with some teams and yacht clubs calling it the worst protocol in the history of the event.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Golden Gate Yacht Club (GGYC) filed its own challenge for the Cup and then filed a court case asking that CNEV be removed as Challenger of Record as being unqualified under the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC also asked that it be named as the rightful Challenger of Record, being the first club to file a conforming challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] There followed a long and acrimonious legal battle, with the New York Court of Appeals finally deciding on April 2, 2009, that CNEV did not qualify as valid challenger, and that the GGYC was thus the rightful Challenger of Record.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Following its successful defense of the Cup on July 3, 2007, Société Nautique de Genève (SNG) accepted a challenge for the 33rd America's Cup from Club Náutico Español de Vela (CNEV), a newly formed yacht club, created for the purpose of challenging for the Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] CNEV had no boats, no clubhouse, only four members (vice presidents of the Spanish Sailing Federation), and had never run a regatta of any type.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On July 5, 2007 SNG and CNEV released the protocols for the next Cup regatta.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The protocol was the subject of much criticism, with some teams and yacht clubs calling it the worst protocol in the history of the event.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Golden Gate Yacht Club (GGYC) initiated legal action against SNG in the New York Supreme Court (the court of first instance) alleging violations of the Deed of Gift of the America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] (New York courts decide disputes regarding the terms of the Deed of Gift because the America's Cup is held under the terms of a charitable legal trust established under New York law).
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The suit alleged that CNEV did not meet the terms of the Deed of Gift as a legitimate yacht club that would qualify to be the challenger of record, in particular because it had never held an annual regatta, which, according to GGYC, was a requirement under the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] At the same time, GGYC issued a challenge for the Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Because of the precedent set in the 1988 America's Cup where San Diego Yacht Club defended against a monohull yacht with a catamaran, any non mutual-consent challenger must specify the largest multi-hull possible under the terms of the Deed of Gift, if it is to have any chance of winning.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Consequently, GGYC specified its yacht as having a 90-ft length-waterline, and 90-ft beam.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] As the legal proceedings progressed, SNG continued to work with the other teams on the protocol, and by December 2007 twelve challengers had met the entry deadline and were preparing to race in a multi-challenge 33rd America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] But despite extensive negotiations and proposals made by both sides, GGYC and SNG were unable to agree upon a mutual consent Protocol.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The lawsuit therefore continued and the court ruled in favor of GGYC on November 27, 2007, holding that CNEV was not a valid challenger, and declaring GGYC the proper and legal challenger.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] SNG was instructed to meet GGYC's challenge under the Deed of Gift terms unless they could agree on other terms by mutual consent.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] SNG appealed the decision against CNEV, and on July 29, 2008, the Appellate Division of the New York Supreme Court 2008 reversed the lower court ruling in a 3–2 decision.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The lower court had ruled in favor of GGYC because CNEV had not held an annual regatta when it filed its challenge for the Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] But the Appellate Division ruled that the phrase "having for its annual regatta," as used in the Deed of Gift, is ambiguous.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Pending the outcome of the litigation, SNG had set a deadline of December 15, 2008 for entries in the 33rd America's Cup regatta.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On December 8, 2008 GGYC sent a letter to SNG to inform them that GGYC would not submit an entry since it did not consider SNG's regatta "a legitimate America's Cup" and vowed to focus on winning the legal case in the New York Court of Appeals.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] A number of organizations submitted *amicus curiae* briefs to the court.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] In particular, on December 31, 2008, the New York Yacht Club (NYYC), the oldest and longest holder of the America's Cup, filed a brief supporting GGYC's position.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On April 2, 2009, the New York Court of Appeals in Albany, New York (the court of last instance) decided 6–0 in favor of GGYC, holding that a yacht club could not qualify as challenger unless it had held at least one annual regatta prior to its challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Indeed, despite various calls for negotiation, it had been apparent for some time that the provisions of the Deed of Gift would likely govern the match, and, further, that the parties did not agree on the interpretation of certain provisions of the Deed of Gift or of the court decision.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] In March 2008, the parties had attempted to agree on dates for the races.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] SNG took the position that it was entitled to a 10-month period to prepare for the race and, because it was based in the Northern Hemisphere, the races could not take place until May 2009.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC took the position that the 10-month notice period should run from the November 2007, when the court of first instance ruled that CNEV was not a valid challenger, so the races should take place in October 2008.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Despite various attempts, the parties were unable to agree on the dates and on May 12, 2008, the New York Supreme Court issued an order setting the date at 10 months after that date.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The 10-month delay was held to have been suspended during the appeals process and was reinstated by the final April 2, 2009 decision of the New York Court of Appeals.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] However, SNG refused to accept a race in February 2010, arguing again that the deed did not permit racing in the Northern Hemisphere until May.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC forced a court session and, on May 14, 2009, the court ruled from the bench that the race must take place in February 2010, unless another date was mutually agreed to.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Though the date was now set, dispute persisted regarding the venue.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC maintained that without mutual consent, the defender must specify a deed-legal venue, which in February would mean the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Under the terms of the Court order, if SNG did not specify a venue six months before the match, the venue would default to Valencia.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] In August 2009 SNG announced that the event would be based in the Northern Hemisphere at Al Hamra Village in the Ras al-Khaimah emirate of the United Arab Emirates.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC immediately replied that Ras al-Khaimah was not a Deed Legal Venue.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Unless GGYC agreed to some other location in the Northern Hemisphere, the race must take place in the Southern Hemisphere, because the venue must comply with the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Indeed, said GGYC, the expression "or any other location" in the April 2 court order could not be interpreted literally, because it could not extend to a venue like the Colorado River or Walden Pond.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Given that the literal meaning could not apply, the order must be interpreted consistent with the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On October 27, 2009, Justice Shirley Kornreich ruled from the bench that Ras al-Khaimah, United Arab Emirates was not a deed legal venue and that the race must take place either in Valencia or in a Southern Hemisphere venue.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] In early November, SNG wrote to the court stating that it would hold the race in February in Valencia, Spain., and at the same time, they appealed the decision to the Appellate Division of the New York Supreme Court.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The appeal was denied on December 15, 2009.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On July 14, 2009, GGYC filed a motion with the court asking that SNG be found in contempt for changing the rules for the match in secret to allow them to build a boat with powered winches and moveable ballast which were allegedly illegal under the SNG rules that should apply to the race.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On July 29, 2009, the court issued its decision regarding these matters.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The court refused to hold Alinghi in contempt.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The court ruled that the Deed of Gift does not specify any restrictions on the construction of the yachts.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Provided that the boats are propelled by sails, auxiliary power can be used for winches etc.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The court also ordered a hearing in order to determine the date on which GGYC could reasonably be compelled to produce the Custom House Certificate for its yacht.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On September 2, 2009, GGYC filed an appeal against this decision.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On September 18, 2009, pursuant to its July 29, 2009, decision and following the hearing arising from that decision, the court ruled that the design and construction of the challenger's vessel was not frozen at the time of the challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Thus GGYC could continue to modify and to develop its yacht.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Custom House Registry referred to in the Deed of Gift (now called a Certificate of Documentation-COD) had to be delivered two weeks prior to the first race.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Court stated: "It is not only advances in technology, but the unsportsmanlike behavior of Golden Gate that has resulted in substantially reducing SNG's advantage as originally contemplated by the Deed.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On August 6, 2009, SNG sent a letter to GGYC, containing the measurement procedures for the yachts.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC did not accept these procedures, in particular because the SNG procedure would include the rudders in the LWL measurement and thus result in GGYC's boat *BMW Oracle Racing 90* being disqualified.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC requested the court to declare that the measurement procedure proposed by SNG was not valid (in particular the rudders should not be included when measuring length on the load waterline).
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On October 30, 2009, the court ruled that the rudders should not be included for the measurement of the Load Water Line Length (GGYC's position).
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] SNG appealed that ruling, but the appeal was denied on December 15, 2009.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC also argued that the rules that should apply to the race must be the SNG rules that were in force when GGYC filed its challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Otherwise, said GGYC, SNG could arbitrarily change the rules so as to make it impossible for the challenger to win.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] For example, said GGYC, the modified rules could specify that the challenger would have to race while dragging an anchor.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] According to GGYC, it did not make sense to envisage that the rules could be changed after the challenge was issued, since the challenger based its challenge on SNG's rules at the time of the challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC also challenged certain provisions of the agreement between ISAF and SNG, in particular concerning the powers of the jury.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Further, the court ordered the nomination of a panel of three independent experts who had sat on an America's Cup jury in the past in order to resolve certain outstanding issues.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On December 4, 2009, it was announced that the international jury had been named.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The Notice of Race that was published on November 10, 2009, specified, among other things, that the races would not take place if the wind exceeded 15 knots (28 km/h) or the waves were taller than 1 meter.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] A draft amended Notice of Race and draft Sailing instructions were published on January 8, 2010.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The final versions were published on January 19, 2010.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC requested that the International Jury be convened as soon as possible to negate or revise the biased provisions before the races.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC subsequently requested that the International Jury also consider certain issues related to the measurement rules.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On February 2, 2010, the International Jury rejected GGYC's requests for redress regarding the measurement procedure.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The jury held that the maximum amount of moveable ballast had to be on board when the boat was measured and that it had to be equally distributed laterally, but that no other restrictions would apply.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] It ordered the Notice of Race to be modified to make it clear that the Deed of Gift took precedence and that the Notice of Race and Sailing Instructions could not override the Racing Rules of Sailing.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On January 28, 2010, GGYC announced that it had requested that the International Jury allow it to employ a friction-reduction system that involved discharging liquids in the water.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC stated that friction-reduction systems had been explicitly allowed at SNG's request, so it was not appropriate for SNG to attempt to restrict such systems.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] According to SNG, the discharge of liquids by GGYC's yacht would violate reasonable environmental protection measures incorporated in the Sailing Instructions.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On February 2, 2010, the International Jury decided that friction-reduction systems would be allowed provided that applicable environmental laws were not violated.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On December 22, 2009, GGYC sent a letter to SNG expressing concern about SNG's apparent interpretation of the "constructed in country" provisions of the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] According to GGYC, it appeared that SNG's team intended to use sails constructed in Minden, Nevada, USA, and that this would constitute a direct infringement of the clear terms of the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] GGYC requested that SNG clarify the matter within five days.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] SNG stated that, if GGYC's interpretation were followed, then SNG would have similar concerns regarding a number of items of equipment on board GGYC's yacht.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] SNG also stated that it was concerned that the rig of GGYC's yacht was not as described in the challenge documents dated July 11, 2007.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The proposed meeting took place on 12 and 13 January 2010, but no agreements were reached.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On January 12, 2010, GGYC opened an action in the New York Supreme Court, asking the Court to enter an order declaring that the sails must be constructed in the country where the competing yacht resides and that SNG's apparent use of "3DL" sails would violate the Deed of Gift.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On January 22, 2010, SNG replied to GGYC's allegations.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] According to SNG, the provisions of the Deed of Gift regarding in-country construction do not apply to sails, and, in any case, the sails of its yacht Alinghi 5 were constructed in Switzerland from parts obtained in the USA.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Further, SNG alleged that GGYC's yacht USA itself violated the provisions of the Deed of Gift because it was designed in France and key components were designed and made outside the USA.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Also, SNG alleged that USA 17 was not a sloop and therefore was not consistent with the description provided in the challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Finally, SNG argued that it would be premature for the court to decide such matters before the regatta for procedural reasons; in particular following the precedent set during the 1988 America's Cup, the matter should be decided after the race, if the loser wished to raise it.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On 27 January 2010, GGYC submitted its reply to SNG's allegations.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Essentially, GGYC pressed its case and stated that its yacht had been constructed in the US and was sloop-rigged.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On January 29, 2010, Justice Kornreich of the New York Supreme Court informed the parties via telephone conference that she would not hear the complaint regarding the constructed in country requirement before the match scheduled to begin on 8 February.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The America's Cup races then took place in February 2010 but with several legal actions still awaiting decisions from the courts.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On 26 March 2010, BMW Oracle Racing announced that the parties had signed an agreement putting an end to all litigation which included GGYC Breach of Fiduciary Duty claim against SNG as well as all other claims relating to the legality of certain construction details of Alinghi V and USA-17.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The agreement also included the transfer of various intellectual property rights such as the americascup.com web site and some physical assets to GGYC in their new role as trustee of the America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] BMW Oracle Racing launched a 90-foot (27 m) trimaran in August 2008 in Anacortes, Washington.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] After three weeks of shakedown cruises, the boat was shipped to San Diego, California where it underwent development for the next fourteen months.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Initially known as *BMW Oracle Racing 90* (BOR90), the yacht was renamed *USA 17* upon launch in Valencia conforming with the notice of challenge.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The boat was extensively modified during the time in San Diego, most notably in replacing the outer floats, adding powered hydraulics, and fitting a rigid wing sail.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] At the end of December 2009, the boat was shipped to Valencia, where it arrived on January 4, 2010.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] After its win in the first race, most observers stated that the rigid wing sail had provided USA with a decisive advantage.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Alinghi built a catamaran at a boatyard in Villeneuve, Switzerland, called *Alinghi 5* which was 90-foot (27 m) on the waterline with a bowsprit that makes it "about 120-foot (37 m) overall." Somewhat controversially, A5 introduced an engine to power hydraulics.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] It was launched on July 8, 2009, being lifted from the construction shed in Villeneuve by a Mil Mi-26 helicopter and carried thereby to Lake Geneva.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] On August 7, 2009, the same type of helicopter transported the boat from Lake Geneva to Genoa, Italy.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] At the end of September 2009, the boat was shipped to Ras al Khaimah.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] At the end of December 2009, the boat was shipped to Valencia, where it arrived on January 5, 2010.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Racing was scheduled to start on February 8, 2010, but unsteady wind conditions caused the first start attempt to be postponed, and the second attempt on February 10, 2010, was aborted due to rough sea conditions.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] After the conclusion of the second race, Principal Race Officer (PRO) Harold Bennett commented that he had encountered problems in starting Race 2.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The original Race Instructions issued by the SNG Race Committee (RC) defined the maximum allowed wave height, maximum wind velocity and maximum variation of wind direction across the course in order for a race to be started and completed.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] It is unusual for specific weather conditions to be inserted in the race instructions because this is usually left to the discretion of the PRO to start a race in conditions which are deemed to be safe and/or allow the race to be completed within the time limit.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The consensus of most of the commentators at the time was that the wind conditions defined in the race instructions were artificially low and designed to favour Alinghi 5 which was generally thought to have a better performance than USA 17 in light airs.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The competitors had been waiting on the water for close to four hours.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] As the 16:30 deadline for starting a race approached, Bennett ordered the postponement to be taken down indicating that a race starting sequence would soon commence.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] The SNG Race Committee refused to follow this direction, and left the bridge, moving below decks.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] In order to continue Bennett had to ask Tom Ehman, the BOR representative on board the committee boat plus a support boat driver to assist with the raising and lowering of flags to complete the start sequence.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] "I have never seen such disgraceful behavior on a committee boat, trying to influence the PRO to the point of ordering me to stop the [start] sequence", wrote Bennett.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] As detailed above, on 26 March 2010 BMW Oracle Racing announced that agreement had been reached between GGYC and SNG to drop all remaining litigation hence eliminating the prospect of post-race legal disputes.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] Ten syndicates took part in the regatta which used boats provided by Team New Zealand and BMW Oracle Racing.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] This initial event was then expanded into the Louis Vuitton Trophy series of events which started in November 2009.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] These events were designed to be low cost and keep syndicates active while waiting for the 34th America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] After the conclusion of the second race Club Nautico di Roma represented by the sailing team Mascalzone Latino, a longtime supporter of BMW Oracle, was named the challenger of record.
[src:catamaran/33rd-america-s-cup] BMW Oracle Racing promised a multi-challenger regatta.
[src:catamaran/ac72] The **AC72** (**America's Cup 72 class**) is a class of catamarans with wingsails and hydrofoils, built to a box rule for yachts competing in the 2013 Louis Vuitton and the America's Cup races.
[src:catamaran/ac72] The class was subsequently replaced by the smaller AC50 class.
[src:catamaran/ac72] Following the 2010 America's Cup, where the Golden Gate Yacht Club's *USA 17* trimaran defeated the catamaran *Alinghi 5*, it was decided by the winners that the next America's Cup competition would be sailed in catamarans in the hope of making the sport more attractive to television audiences.
[src:catamaran/ac72] At the same time a smaller sister class, the AC45, was developed to allow teams to practice and adjust to the new formula as well as create a greater exposure of sailing to the general public with the America's Cup World Series.
[src:catamaran/ac72] Using foils for the first time in the America's Cup, the AC72 was expected to sail faster than the wind: upwind at 1.2 times the speed of the true wind, and downwind at 1.6 times the speed of the true wind.
[src:catamaran/ac72] In fact it proved even faster, averaging about 1.8 times the speed of the wind with peaks slightly over 2.3.
[src:catamaran/ac72] A multiple of 2.79 times wind speed was achieved by Emirates Team New Zealand in practice, as they sailed at 44.15 knots (81 km/h, 50 mph) in 15.8 knots of wind on July 18, 2013.
[src:catamaran/ac72] Typical racing speeds are over 30 knots (55 km/h, 34 mph) with the boats capable of attaining well over 40 knots (74 km/h, 46 mph) in the right conditions.
[src:catamaran/ac72] The fastest race speed recorded was 47.57 knots (88 km/h, 55 mph) in 21.8 knots of wind (2.2 times the wind speed) on September 24, 2013, by Emirates Team New Zealand.
[src:catamaran/ac72] The boats have been used in the 2013 Louis Vuitton Cup and the 2013 America's Cup.
[src:catamaran/ac72] By mid-June 2013, all boats had "lined up" and conducted trials against each other on the planned race track in San Francisco Bay, notably Oracle Team USA vs.
[src:catamaran/ac72] Artemis Racing and Emirates Team New Zealand vs.
[src:catamaran/ac72] On 17 October 2012, Oracle Racing's AC72 pitchpoled (somersaulted) and capsized, causing severe damage to the yacht.
[src:catamaran/ac72] The wingsail was completely destroyed while being swept under the Golden Gate Bridge by a strong ebb tide.
[src:catamaran/ac72] On 9 May 2013, Artemis Racing's AC72 pitchpoled and broke apart, resulting in the death of crew member Andrew Simpson.
[src:catamaran/ac72] The other two teams, Luna Rossa Challenge, and Team New Zealand, both suffered minor setbacks, including hitting seals and damaging their wing sails, resulting in loss of sailing time.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:catamaran/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:catamaran/aft] This **list of ship directions** provides succinct definitions for terms applying to spatial orientation in a marine environment or location on a vessel, such as *fore*, *aft*, *astern*, *aboard*, or *topside*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:catamaran/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:catamaran/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] A **catamaran** (/ˌkætəməˈræn/) (informally, a "cat") is a watercraft with two parallel hulls of equal size.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The wide distance between a catamaran's hulls imparts stability through resistance to rolling and overturning; no ballast is required.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans typically have less hull volume, smaller displacement, and shallower draft (draught) than monohulls of comparable length.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The two hulls combined also often have a smaller hydrodynamic resistance than comparable monohulls, requiring less propulsive power from either sails or motors.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The catamaran's wider stance on the water can reduce both heeling and wave-induced motion, as compared with a monohull, and can give reduced wakes.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans were invented by the Austronesian peoples, and enabled their expansion to the islands of the Indian and Pacific Oceans.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans range in size from small sailing or rowing vessels to large naval ships and roll-on/roll-off car ferries.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The structure connecting a catamaran's two hulls ranges from a simple frame strung with webbing to support the crew to a bridging superstructure incorporating extensive cabin or cargo space.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans from Oceania and Maritime Southeast Asia became the inspiration for modern catamarans.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Until the 20th century catamaran development focused primarily on sail-driven concepts.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The word "catamaran" is derived from the Tamil word, *kattumaram* (கட்டுமரம்), which means "logs bound together" and is a type of single-hulled raft made of three to seven tree trunks lashed together.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The term has evolved in English usage to refer to unrelated twin-hulled vessels.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamaran-type vessels were an early technology of the Austronesian peoples.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Early researchers like Heine-Geldern (1932) and Hornell (1943) once believed that catamarans evolved from outrigger canoes, but modern authors specializing in Austronesian cultures like Doran (1981) and Mahdi (1988) now believe it to be the opposite.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Two canoes bound together developed directly from minimal raft technologies of two logs tied together.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Over time, the twin-hulled canoe form developed into the asymmetric double canoe, where one hull is smaller than the other.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Eventually the smaller hull became the prototype outrigger, giving way to the single outrigger canoe, then to the reversible single outrigger canoe.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Finally, the single outrigger types developed into the double outrigger canoe (or trimarans).
[src:catamaran/catamaran] This would also explain why older Austronesian populations in Island Southeast Asia tend to favor double outrigger canoes, as it keeps the boats stable when tacking.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] But they still have small regions where catamarans and single-outrigger canoes are still used.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] In contrast, more distant outlying descendant populations in Oceania, Madagascar, and the Comoros, retained the twin-hull and the single outrigger canoe types, but the technology for double outriggers never reached them (although it exists in western Melanesia).
[src:catamaran/catamaran] To deal with the problem of the instability of the boat when the outrigger faces leeward when tacking, they instead developed the shunting technique in sailing, in conjunction with reversible single-outriggers.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Despite their being the more "primitive form" of outrigger canoes, they were nonetheless effective, allowing seafaring Polynesians to voyage to distant Pacific islands.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The first documented example of twin-hulled sailing craft in Europe was designed by William Petty in 1662 to sail faster, in shallower waters, in lighter wind, and with fewer crew than other vessels of the time.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] However, the unusual design met with skepticism and was not a commercial success.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The design remained relatively unused in the West for almost 160 years until the early 19th century, when the Englishman Mayflower F.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Crisp built a two-hulled merchant ship in Rangoon, Burma.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Crisp described it as "a fast sailing fine sea boat; she traded during the monsoon between Rangoon and the Tenasserim Provinces for several years".
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Later that century, the American Nathanael Herreshoff constructed a twin-hulled sailing boat of his own design (US Pat.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The craft, *Amaryllis*, raced at her maiden regatta on June 22, 1876, and performed exceedingly well.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Her debut demonstrated the distinct performance advantages afforded to catamarans over the standard monohulls.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] It was as a result of this event, the Centennial Regatta of the New York Yacht Club, that catamarans were barred from regular sailing classes, and this remained the case until the 1970s.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] On June 6, 1882, three catamarans from the Southern Yacht Club of New Orleans raced a 15 nm course on Lake Pontchartrain and the winning boat in the catamaran class, *Nip and Tuck*, beat the fastest sloop's time by over five minutes.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] In 1916, Leonardo Torres Quevedo patented a multihull steel vessel named *Binave* (Twin Ship), a new type of catamaran which was constructed and tested in Bilbao (Spain) in 1918.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The innovative design introduced a flexible structural system to counteract sea-induced torsion, included two 30 HP Hispano-Suiza marine engines and could modify its configuration when sailing, positioning two rudders at the stern of each float, with the propellers also placed aft.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] In 1936, Eric de Bisschop built a Polynesian "double canoe" in Hawaii and sailed it home to a hero's welcome in France.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] In 1939, he published his experiences in a book, *Kaimiloa*, which was translated into English in 1940.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Roland and Francis Prout experimented with catamarans in 1949 and converted their 1935 boat factory in Canvey Island, Essex (England), to catamaran production in 1954.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Their *Shearwater* catamarans easily won races against monohulls.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] *Yellow Bird,* a 1956-built *Shearwater III*, raced successfully by Francis Prout in the 1960s, is in the collection of the National Maritime Museum Cornwall.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Prout Catamarans, Ltd. designed a mast aft rig with the mast aft of midships to support an enlarged jib—more than twice the size of the design's reduced mainsail; it was produced as the *Snowgoose* model.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The claimed advantage of this sail plan was to diminish any tendency for the bows of the vessel to dig in.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] In the mid-twentieth century, beachcats became a widespread category of sailing catamarans, owing to their ease of launching and mass production.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] In California, a maker of surfboards, Hobie Alter, produced the 250-pound (110 kg) Hobie 14 in 1967, and two years later the larger and even more successful Hobie 16.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] As of 2016, the Hobie 16 was still being produced with more than 100,000 having been manufactured.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans were introduced to Olympic sailing in 1976.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The two-handed Tornado catamaran was selected for the multihull discipline in the Olympic Games from 1976 through 2008.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The foiling Nacra 17 was used in the Tokyo 2020 Olympics, which were held in 2021; after the 2015 adoption of the Nacra 15 as a Youth World Championships class and as a new class for the Youth Olympic Games.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans have two distinct primary performance characteristics that distinguish them from displacement monohull vessels: lower resistance to passage through the water and greater stability (initial resistance to capsize).
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Choosing between a monohull and catamaran configuration includes considerations of carrying capacity, speed, and efficiency.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] At low to moderate speeds, a lightweight catamaran hull experiences resistance to passage through water that is approximately proportional to its speed.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] A displacement monohull has the same relationship at low speed since resistance is almost entirely due to surface friction.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] For sailing catamarans, low forward resistance allows the sails to derive power from attached flow, their most efficient mode—analogous to a wing—leading to the use of wingsails in racing craft.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Catamarans rely primarily on form stability to resist heeling and capsize.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Comparison of heeling stability of a rectangular-cross section monohull of beam, *B*, compared with two catamaran hulls of width *B*/2, separated by a distance, 2×*B*, determines that the catamaran has an initial resistance to heeling that is seven times that of the monohull.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Compared with a monohull, a cruising catamaran sailboat has a high initial resistance to heeling and capsize—a fifty-footer requires four times the force to initiate a capsize than an equivalent monohull.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] One measure of the trade-off between speed and carrying capacity is the displacement Froude number (FnV), compared with *calm water transportation efficiency*.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] FnV applies when the waterline length is too speed-dependent to be meaningful—as with a planing hull.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Large merchant vessels have a FnV between one and zero, whereas higher-performance powered catamarans may approach 2.5, denoting a higher speed per unit volume for catamarans.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Each type of vessel has a corresponding calm water transportation efficiency, with large transport ships being in the range of 100–1,000, compared with 11-18 for transport catamarans, denoting a higher efficiency per unit of payload for monohulls.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] Two advances over the traditional catamaran are the *small-waterplane-area twin hull* (SWATH) and the *wave-piercing* configuration—the latter having become a widely favored design.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] SWATH reduces wave-generating resistance by moving displacement volume below the waterline, using a pair of tubular, submarine-like hulls, connected by pylons to the bridge deck with a narrow waterline cross-section.
[src:catamaran/catamaran] The submerged hulls are minimally affected by waves.
